            "answer_text": "Its simple, if you understand how the technology works. To track a phone it must be able to send and receive signals. A phone may be tracked by either wireless signal, wifi signal, or gps signal. If you were to block or interfere the signal from being sent or recieved, the phone cannot be tracked. Signals are electromagnetic waves, it can travel thru all sorts of things, but not everything. A dense enough object can absorb the signal being transmitted or recieved, also enough \u201cstuff\u201d in between the phone and the tower can also block signals. Signals have the most trouble traveling thru concrete, metal, and the earth. This is why you often have little or no reception in tall/large buildings, parking structures, underground, or inside a building with a continuous metal roof. Knowing how the phone works gives you clues how to block its signal. Storing it inside a metal box for example, will block the signal from being transmitted or an incoming one to be received. So it's simple- wrap it in some metal (ie, alumnium foil)- and the phone cannot be traced until you remove it from the metal container. Your location can still be seen when you use the phone outside the metal container, and leaving the phone in the container will also drain its battery super fast because its trying constantly to connect to a tower. A more practical solution is get a new phone with a new number. There\u2019s no law against doing that, and if the cops want to track the new phone and number they'll need to know what number and a court order. The number may be unlisted and private. This is why most criminals have a bunch of burner phones- if they suspect the cops are on to them they'll ditch it for another one. ",
